    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-12-20T08:35:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-12-20T08:35:00-05:00" n="465"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d465">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">891.51A/12–2044: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Iran</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Morris</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tehran</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-12-20T17:00:00+03:25"
                            >December 20, 1944—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received December 21—2:53 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>939. Foreign Minister Entezam<note n="46" xml:id="d465fn46">Nasrollah Entezam,
                        formerly Minister of Communications, became Minister for Foreign Affairs on
                        December 7, 1944.</note> told me today that Millspaugh and Prime Minister
                    Bayat have reached agreement by which Millspaugh will accept repeal of his
                    economic powers and remain to administer financial affairs under authority
                    granted by law of 21 Aban.</p>
                <p>Mossadegh yesterday introduced into Majlis bill to repeal all Millspaugh powers,
                    including those granted by law of 21 Aban and establish <pb facs="0454" n="442"
                        xml:id="pg_442"/> committee of 5 men to supervise operations of Ministry of
                    Finance. His attempt to rush this through failed, however, and Majlis has as yet
                    taken no action on it. Entezam expects that Prime Minister’s bill reported in my
                    932, December 15 will be adopted.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Morris</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
